Feeling their attacks upon Neil Gorsuch are falling flat and seeing his nomination as an inevitably, some Democrats are seeking to play a weak hand to make a deal on the Supreme Court nominee’s confirmation. 
According to Politico , “the deal Democrats would be most likely to pursue, the sources said, would be to allow confirmation of Gorsuch in exchange for a commitment from Republicans not to kill the filibuster for a subsequent vacancy during President Donald Trump’s term.” 
A Republican agreement to such a deal would be a making-lemonade-out-of-lemons for Democrats desperate for a win. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-0'); }); 
According to Politico’s sources familiar with the deal, Democrats fear that they will come out of the Gorsuch confirmation not only empty-handed but in a poor position to prevent Trump from nominating another judge along the lines of Gorsuch in the likely event another Supreme Court opening occurs during Trump’s presidency. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1464204305408-0'); }); 
That would be especially bad for the Democrats if the next Trump nominee would be replacing a Supreme Court liberal such as Ruth Bader Ginsburg, as it would shift the balance of the court squarely to the Conservatives. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-1'); }); 
“Killing the filibuster” would mean the Senate would become a majority-rule chamber like the House. And right now that majority is Republican. 
It is therefore a measure many Republicans, including President Trump and many House Republicans, would love to see the Senate take, especially on Supreme Court nominees. 
However, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell is said to be loathe to kill the filibuster, both because he is a traditionalist and because he – like many others – foresees the day when Republicans will be in the minority. 
As Ed Morrissey of Hot Air once wrote: googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-2'); }); 
The only thing keeping the Senate minority relevant is the legislative filibuster, which is why House Republicans want it eliminated. However, McConnell’s been around long enough to know that it’s a suicidal strategy. Yes, Republicans would be able to slam their entire agenda through Congress to the White House, but that will be true of Democrats at some point when they regain power in Washington. That’s when, not if, and McConnell knows it. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1448050117784-4'); }); googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1464204305408-1'); }); 
Yet if McConnell allows his reluctance to kill the filibuster to lead him to accept this deal, it would likely be politically disastrous for him, and for any other Republican should he or she also go along with. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-3'); }); 
Conservative host Mark Levin on his March 22nd program has already called the deal “nuts.” And conservative website Legal Insurrrection has asked “Gorsuch is likely to be confirmed with or without a deal, so there’s seemingly zero reason for Senate Republicans to even entertain such a deal if it was being discussed.” 
Any deal that allows Gorsuch to ascend to the SCOTUS would be a hard-sell to many on the Left as well, even if it would benefit them down the road. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-4'); });
